surveys in the vicinities of pedregal and san cristóbal for the route of the tehuantepec railway had reported oil seepage from the ground so in april  he ordered his manager in mexico to secure prospecting options on all land for miles around pearson built a refinery pipelines and port facilities to handle the oil in – but his company didnt make a major oil strike until  in the same year one of pearsons oil strikes caught fire and burned out of control for eight weeks destroying the entire oil field in  pearson founded the compañía mexicana de petróleo el aguila sa mexican eagle oil company in mexico to take over s pearson and sons oil interests this followed pearsons creation of whitehall securities corporation ltd in the uk in  to manage all of s pearson and sons investments outside the oil industry pearsons prospecting continued without success until  december  when a well on the gulf of mexico coast between veracruz and tampico struck oil that flowed at a rate of  barrels per day this single well turned the fortunes of pearsons oil business within a few years he was one of mexicos two major oil magnates the other being doheny other oil companies from the usa and europe had entered the mexican oil industry but doheny and pearsons companies remained preeminent until after the first world war in  the mexican revolution overthrew the díaz dictatorship that had favoured pearson ending the civil engineering contracts for which he had first become involved in mexico however pearson had exclusive rights to prospect for oil in several mexican states and by  the company  acres  km of prospecting rights  miles  kilometres of pipeline two refineries the second being newly built at tampico and storage for seven million barrels of oil by june  mexican eagle was the largest company in the pearson group with net assets valued at £ million however in december  pearson claimed in a letter to the uk chancellor of the exchequer david lloyd george that mexican eagle was worth £ million mexican eagle was the largest contributor to the pearson groups valuation in  of £ million which made it the seventh largest business in the uk and among the  largest businesses in the world by  the pearson group was worth £ million of which in june of that year mexican eagle made up £ million to what extent this represents a growth in value must be considered against the degree of inflation that took place in the first world war however in  the pearson groups share value was £ million of which mexican eagle made up £ million this made mexican eagle roughly the equal of burmah oil and far bigger than the anglopersian oil company or shell transport and trading buyout offers and eventual saleedit in  pearson declined an offer from the texas oil company offered to buy his oil interests in  and  he declined buyout bids from royal dutch shell and in  and  he declined bids from standard oil of new jersey by  pearson was keen to sell but the uk government persuaded him for strategic reasons not to do so pearson asked the uk government to buy  of his oil interests but it responded in  by imposing restrictions that prevented him from transferring ownership as long as the war continued the constitution of mexico adopted in  nationalised oil deposits in october  a month before the armistice calouste gulbenkian started negotiations with pearson for royal dutch shell to buy mexican eagle on april   the royal dutch petroleum company and the shell transport and trading company jointly bought mexican eagle for us million mexican eagle was the dominant firm in the mexican petroleum industry until march   when the government of lázaro cárdenas nationalized it along with all other foreignowned oil interests to create petróleos mexicanos pemex el aguila formally dissolved itself on may   eagle oil and shipping companyedit main article eagle oil and shipping company pearson started to acquire steam tankers to carry the oil that he hoped to produce armstrong whitworth on the river tyne launched ss san cristobal  tons in  and swan hunter also on tyneside launched ss san antonio  tons in  pearson also bought ss james brand  tons which had been built by armstrong whitworth in  and renamed her san bernardo in  pearson founded the eagle oil transport company in the uk to take over his ships and carry mexican eagles products and the anglomexican petroleum company in the uk to sell mexican eagles products outside mexico eagle oil transport immediately ordered  modern steam tankers at a cost of £ million eagle oil transport lost a number of ships to enemy action in the first world war after the first world war eagle oil transport renewed and expanded its fleet it bought numerous new tankers including six of about  tons each when royal dutch shell bought pearsons oil interests that included eagle oil transport and anglosaxon petroleum as well as mexical eagle petroleum in about  the eagle oil transport company was renamed the eagle oil and shipping company in about  the company started adding a new generation of motor tankers of about  tons each eagle oil and shipping was registered in the united kingdom therefore after  although the mexican government had nationalised mexican eagle petroleum eagle oil and shipping remained a subsidiary of royal dutch shell after  the fleet continued to carry oil from the gulf of mexico to the uk during the second world war the company played an important role in supplying petroleum and petroleum products to the united kingdom oil tankers were a particular target in germanys economic warfare against the uk enemy action sank  eagle oils ships and killed at least  officers men and dems gunners serving aboard them mv san demetrio reached the clyde in  with a cargo of aviation spirit despite having been damaged by shellfire from the admiral scheer among the ships lost was mv san demetrio  tons which was famous for surviving a naval bombardment by the german heavy cruiser admiral scheer in  that set the tanker on fire san demetrio was repaired and returned to service but the uboat u torpedoed and sank her in the western atlantic off virginia in  with the loss of  lives in  the ministry of war transport placed a number of empire ships under eagle oil and shippings management one was sunk by enemy action in  but after the war the company bought two of the surviving ships from the ministry the company also bought two t tankers that had been built in the usa the company further renewed its fleet with  new ships between  and  and maximum tonnages steadily rose towards the end of the decade the royal dutch shell parent group absorbed eagle oil and shipping in  notesedit  godley  pp    a b c d godley  p   a b godley  p   godley  p   a b godley  p   a b godley  p   godley  p   a b c d godley  p   godley  p   watkins thayer the petroleum industry of mexico san josé state university   a b c godley  p   a b godley  p   godley  p   godley  p   godley  p   a b c d e f godley  p   a b godley  p    oil deal royal dutch and shell companies buy mexican eagle stock new york times  though the reference says shell oil company now the name of royal dutch shells us subsidiary it also says the price was split  royal dutch shell the exact split of the  royal dutch – shell transport joint venture and their  merger thus the  buyer must have been shell transport not shell oil company  kennedy paul p  big oil company closes its books el aguila of mexico holders vote to dissolve new york times   marconi transatlantic wireless telegraph  form  line cowdray interests to build fleet to carry mexican oil products new york times   godley  pp    lloyds register of shipping london lloyds of london   accessdate requires url help  talbotbooth  p   claes johnny vleggeert nico  ss empire norseman  the wreck site retrieved   further readingedit godley andrew  weetman pearson in mexico and the emergence of a british oil major – reading berkshire henley school of management  accessdate requires url help maurer noel  the empire 